      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B–1 Let {x} denote the distance between the real number x and the nearest integer. For each positive integer n, evaluate",
        "bbox": [
          0.523921568627451,
          0.13454545454545455,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.1787878787878788
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–1 A rectangle, HOMF, has sides HO = 11 and OM = 5. A triangle ABC has H as the intersection of the altitudes, O the center of the circumscribed circle, M the midpoint of BC, and F the foot of the altitude from A. What is the length of BC?",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.13515151515151516,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.20787878787878789
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–2 Players 1, 2, 3, . . .,n are seated around a table, and each has a single penny. Player 1 passes a penny to player 2, who then passes two pennies to player 3. Player 3 then passes one penny to Player 4, who passes two pen- nies to Player 5, and so on, players alternately passing one penny or two to the next player who still has some pennies. A player who runs out of pennies drops out of the game and leaves the table. Find an infinite set of numbers n for which some player ends up with all n pennies.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.21696969696969698,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.36303030303030304
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(Here min(a, b) denotes the minimum of a and b.) B—2 Let f be a twice-differentiable real-valued function sat- isfying",
        "bbox": [
          0.5231372549019608,
          0.23696969696969697,
          0.9184313725490196,
          0.2812121212121212
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "where g(x) ≥ 0 for all real x. Prove that |f (x)| is bounded.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.3193939393939394,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.3490909090909091
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B-3 For each positive integer n, write the sum ∑m=1 1/m in the form pn/qn, where pn and qn are relatively prime positive integers. Determine all n such that 5 does not divide qn.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5231372549019608,
          0.35818181818181816,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.4175757575757576
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Problems_1997_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-3 Evaluate",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.37272727272727274,
          0.18666666666666668,
